ATE_2: 2 ones\n- STATE_3: 3 ones\n- STATE_4: 4 ones\n- STATE_5: 5 ones\n- STATE_6: 6 ones\n- STATE_7: 7 or more ones\n- STATE_DISC: pattern 0111110 detected\n- STATE_FLAG: pattern 01111110 detected\n\nTransitions:\nFrom STATE_i (i=0..5): if in=1 -> STATE_{i+1}, if in=0 -> STATE_0\nFrom STATE_5: if in=1 -> STATE_6, if in=0 -> STATE_DISC\nFrom STATE_6: if in=1 -> STATE_7, if in=0 -> STATE_FLAG\nFrom STATE_7: if in=1 -> STATE_7, if in=0 -> STATE_0\nFrom STATE_DISC: if in=1 -> STATE_1, if in=0 -> STATE_0\nFrom STATE_FLAG: if in=1 -> STATE_1, if in=0 -> STATE_0\n\nOutputs:\n- STATE_7: err = 1\n- STATE_DISC: disc = 1\n- STATE_FLAG: flag = 1\n\nWait, if we are in STATE_DISC (having seen 0111110), the output 'disc' is high. This satisfies the 'one cycle after' requirement because the '0' that completes the pattern is the input that triggers the transition to STATE_DISC, and the output is high while in STATE_DISC.\n\nOne edge case: 'When the FSM is reset, it should be in a state that behaves as though the previous input were 0.' This means we start in STATE_0.\n\nAdvice to avoid syntax error: \n- Ensure all signals are declared as 'logic'.\n- Use 'always @(*)' for combinational logic.\n- Use 'always @(posedge clk)' for sequential logic.\n- Use 'localparam' for state encoding.\n- Match the module interface exactly.",
